Rule.desc: Avoid hiding methods from base classes
Always provide names for threads
Use 'L' instead of 'l' to express 'long' integer constants
Avoid throwing exceptions from static constructors
Avoid never listened private events
Avoid never raised events
Do not return values from events
Event argument classes should extend System.EventArgs
Avoid unused private fields
Avoid parameter swapping when overriding or implementing methods
Ensure that method return values are used
Avoid unused private methods
Avoid using very large methods
Avoid checked, unchecked, fixed and unsafe statements with empty bodies
Avoid initialization statements with empty bodies
Always enclose iteration statements bodies with curly braces
Always enclose using statement body with curly braces
Avoid clearing stack trace while rethrowing exceptions
Avoid assignment within a condition
Avoid conditional statements with empty bodies
Avoid try, catch, finally and using statements with empty bodies
Do not use floating point variables as loop indices
Avoid increment and decrement statements which have no effect
Review '?:' operator for potential misuse
Do not increment or decrement on the same variable over multiple nested 'for' loop statements
Do not compare value types to null
Avoid non-iterable loops
Do not use bitwise operators on bool operands
Avoid confusing assignments to constructor arguments
Check for 'null' when using 'as' operator
Provide 'default:' for each 'switch' statement
Use initializer variable in a condition of 'for' loop
Use initializer variable in 'for' loop iterator section
Avoid inaccessible classes and structs
Do not modify 'for' loop initializer variable in 'for' loop body
Avoid using the unary + operator
Return empty collection instead of null
Do not use an integer outside the range of [0, 31] as the amount of a shift
Avoid wrong indentation of blockless statements
Avoid unreachable code
Avoid unreachable code in condition
Verify FileDialog filter pattern
Do not re-create string from SecureString
Use SecureString instead of String for password
Implement IDeserializationCallback for classes with NonSerialized fields
Do not store non-serializable objects in Session
Use the standard pattern while implementing ISerializable
Avoid lock statements with empty bodies
Always enclose lock statement body with curly braces
Do not catch 'NullReferenceException''
Avoid throwing exceptions from exceptions constructors
Avoid static collections which may lead to memory leakage
Dispose IDisposable local variable
Avoid calling Finalize directly
Avoid throwing exceptions from the Dispose method implementations
Avoid throwing exceptions from finalizers
Method 'Dispose(bool)' in method 'Dispose()' should be called with true and in finalizer with false
IDisposable.Dispose() implementation should call specific methods
Always call Dispose(bool) in finalizer if IDisposable is implemented
In 'Dispose(bool)' use input parameter to check if it is actually disposing
Provide finalizers in types which use resources
Type that implements 'IDisposable' should contain and use field with information about dispose state
Type that implements 'IDisposable' should implement 'Dispose(bool)' method
Call the Dispose method of the base class from the Dispose method in the derived class
Method 'Dispose()' should not be overridable
Implement IDisposable when you provide a destructor (finalizer)
Method 'Dispose(bool)' should be private or protected
Implement IDisposable in types which are using system resources
Avoid throwing exceptions from Equals methods
Avoid throwing exceptions from GetHashCode methods
Avoid throwing exceptions from implicit type conversion operators
Avoid throwing exceptions in equality operators
Compare parameter of Equals(Object) method to null
Override the GetHashCode method whenever you override the Equals method
Do not override operator equality in reference types
Compare parameter type of Equals(Object) method
Override Equals when implementing IComparable
Override Equals when you override operator ==
Overload operators symmetrically
Do not use ReferenceEquals() on value types
Avoid infinite recursive method calls
Do not use value types as arguments of Monitor.Enter and Monitor.Exit
Avoid throwing exceptions from ToString method
Verify number of arguments in Composite Formatting feature
Close file system resource on local variable
Don't use illegal regular expression
Ensure static field is initialized before it is used
Ensure that method body used in ThreadStart/ParameterizedThreadStart is wrapped with 'try/catch'
Do not compare floating-point types for equality
Use TryParse method instead Parse on primitive types
Use String.IsNullOrEmpty to check if a string is null or empty
Do not check whether the result of 'String.IndexOf()' is positive or not
Do not leave code which throws System.NotImplementedException
Ensure that comments do not contain task tags
Do not attempt to deny the SkipVerification security permission
Close database connection local variable
Close database resource local variable
Do not change the RSA/DSA KeySize property
Avoid declaring classes outside namespaces
Do not use hardcoded string for password related parameters
Avoid using insecure algorithms for cryptography
Ensure all exceptions are either logged with a standard logger or rethrown
Use System.Security.Cryptography.RandomNumberGenerator instead of System.Random
Ensure base classes are marked Serializable
Ensure entire graph of object can be serialized
Mark ISerializable.GetObjectData with SecurityPermissionAttribute
Call WriteObjectdata while implementing ISerializable.GetObjectData
Always provide deserialization constructor when ISerializable interface is implemented
Ensure exception classes are marked Serializable
Ensure that readonly property which is a collection does not expose any sensitive information
Ensure that property of collection type implements Add method and indexer
Make sure that type of serialized field/property is compatible with type used in XmlElementAttribute
Remove XmlAttribute from field and properties of comlex types
Always provide default parameterless constructor in xml serialized class
Do not use interface type for xml serialized property or field
Make type used in xml serialization 'public'
Provide setter for xml serialized properties
Avoid calling Thread.Abort()
Avoid calling Thread.Sleep()
Do not hide inherited fields
Avoid unused nested private types
Enforce custom attribute ImmutableAtomic
Call the Finalize method of the base class from the finalizer in the derived class
